### Competitor Content Weaknesses
- All competitors (OPI, Essie, Purluxe, SNS, Manucurist, StyleCraze, BTArtbox) cover the same 4-tone structure (fair/medium/olive/dark) with near-identical shade lists. Content is interchangeable.
- Zero competitors explain **why** a shade fails on a specific tone — they list what works, never why the wrong choice looks bad (the "washed out" or "mannequin hands" problem goes unexplained).
- No competitor addresses **Indian/South Asian/wheatish skin** in a pillar guide — massive editorial gap for a global audience.
- No competitor addresses the **tanning variable** — many readers have skin that changes seasonally and do not know if their nail colour recommendations shift.
- No competitor distinguishes between **skin tone depth** and **undertone temperature** in a way that is genuinely clear. Most conflate them or explain them poorly.
- No competitor answers: **"I know my undertone — now what?"** — the leap from identification to actual shade selection is left to the reader.
- Visual content is universally stock-heavy — no real on-skin shade demonstrations across diverse tones.

### Competitor Gaps — Our Opportunity
- **Unanswered questions:** "Why does this colour wash me out?", "My tone changes with the sun — do my nail colours change too?", "I'm South Asian / wheatish — none of these guides work for me", "What's the difference between warm red and cool red — why does it matter for my skin?", "Is undertone the same as skin tone?", "Do these rules apply to toenails too?"
- **Missing semantic territory:** Seasonal tone shift (summer vs winter skin), the "mannequin hands" failure mode, wheatish / dusky / South Asian terminology, finish interaction (matte vs gloss on different tones), the colour theory logic behind what makes a shade flatter or fail
- **Audience blind spots:** Readers who identify by hair colour + skin tone combo (dark-haired olive skin vs fair redhead), readers who have never found their skin tone in Western beauty categories, readers who want rules they can trust rather than permissive "everything goes" advice

### Strategic Approach
Our differentiation is explaining the **logic**, not just listing the shades. Competitors give lists. We give a framework — the why behind what works — so the reader walks away able to make decisions independently. We are the only guide that acknowledges South Asian / Indian skin tone explicitly in a pillar, and the only guide that addresses the seasonal skin tone shift question. Structure follows the reader's journey: identify → understand undertone → find your tone match → go deeper via spoke posts.

