## AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE

**Blog Gen Instruction:** This section is your primary creative brief. Use this audience data to inform every paragraph, every sentence, every word choice. You are writing for this specific person with this specific intent. Satisfy them completely.

### Intent-Specific Audience Profile
- **Who they are:** Women 18–45, global, mixed nail knowledge. Some have never thought about undertone. Some are experienced nail fans who keep choosing wrong shades. A significant portion are South Asian, East Asian, Latina — underserved by Western beauty guides that default to fair/medium/dark as the only categories.
- **What they want from this post:** A clear framework they can actually apply. Not another list of shades that looks like every other guide. They want to understand the logic so they can make decisions confidently — at the salon, buying online, or swatching at home.
- **What satisfies them:** A guide that explains *why* a colour fails (not just what works), that acknowledges their specific tone exists, that gives them a method to apply — vein test + what to do next — and that links them to deeper guidance for their specific tone without making them scroll through a wall of generic content.
- **What frustrates them:** Generic lists that repeat across 10 different sites. "It depends on your undertone" advice with no follow-through. Guides that only feature fair, medium, olive, dark — nothing for South Asian, wheatish, dusky, or golden-brown tones. Advice that says "anything goes!" when they genuinely want flattering direction. Shade recommendations that looked great on a blonde white influencer but land wrong on their skin.

### Top 5 Pain Points
1. Chose a trending colour (butter yellow, milky white, icy nude) that looked beautiful online but looked wrong on their actual hands — washed out or clashed
2. Cannot identify their undertone confidently — the vein test is confusing, results feel ambiguous
3. Finds their skin tone in Western beauty guides — they're described as "medium" when they identify as wheatish, dusky, or South Asian
4. Bought a nude that looked perfect in the bottle but gave "mannequin hands" on their skin
5. Gets a colour that "works" for their tone on paper but the shade felt flat — they didn't realise finish (matte vs gloss) changes everything

